<HEAD>Proud Bird Takes Aim at Atlantic Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A six-man crew determined to break the record for a trans-Atlantic voyage set off Sunday from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> aboard a $ 6 million speedboat. <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gentry </PERSON>, 57, and his crew passed Ambrose Light just outside <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> at 11:26 a.m. Sunday to start the race across the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Bishop </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> off <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Isles of <LOCATION> Scilly </LOCATION>, race spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON> said. The 110-foot, 11,460 horsepower Gentry-Continental Proud Bird, sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, will attempt to cross the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> in less than 72 hours. The current record time of 3 days, 8 hours and 31 minutes was set in 1986 by Englishman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Branson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Branson </PERSON>, who owns <ORGANIZATION> Virgin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> and several other companies, set his record on June 29, 1986, in the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> Challenger II. It was <PERSON> Branson </PERSON>'s second attempt at the crossing. His first attempt, in May 1985, failed when the original <ORGANIZATION> Virgin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Challenger </ORGANIZATION> sank 138 miles short of the finish. Crew member <PERSON> Jeffery </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, speaking by radio-telephone, said the Proud Bird had passed over the Nantucket Shoals about 3:30 p.m. Sunday. The vessel was cruising at 50 knots through six-foot swells and fog, he said. `` We'd like a little smoother seas,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. `` Basically the autopilot is doing the driving and we're just kind of cruising along,'' he said. However, the boat's size, speed and sea conditions were making for a rough passage. `` It's not a comfy ride. There's a rolling and pitching motion and when you hit these swells. You feel a few inches shorter and like you've been punched in the stomach,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> reported.
