<HEAD>Filipino Rebels Say Washington May be Forced to Send Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist rebels said Sunday that President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has failed to lift the country out of crisis and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may have to send troops to prop up the government. The rebels, who have been battling for power for 20 years, issued a statement on the eve of the president's state of the nation address. Meanwhile, four soldiers, a policeman and two guerrillas were killed in three separate battles across the country during the last 24 hours, the military said Sunday. The rebels said Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> `` can not cover up the basic truth that the Filipino nation remains in deep crisis, that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> control and interference continue to fetter national development, that the nation is being ever more polarized along class and political lines. `` Direct armed intervention by <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> troops is a distinct possibility _ meaning a much bloodier war for the Filipino people _ should the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imperialists judge that the Aquino regime can no longer stop the general advance of the people's democratic revolution and protect strategic American interests.'' Copies of the statement were were delivered to news agencies by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. The front is an umbrella for 12 rebel groups, including the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and its 25,000-member <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. The government gave no official response to the rebels' statement Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> is to address the nation Monday when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reconvenes for its second session after a month-long recess. In the fighting, the army said that on <LOCATION> Panay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, 230 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, communist rebels ambushed and killed four soldiers Saturday. On <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> island, one of three attackers Saturday shot and killed a policeman as he left his home near the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-run </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, about 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Also Saturday, two suspected communist rebels were killed in a gun battle after they wounded a <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> constabulary captain in <LOCATION> Cabanatuan </LOCATION>, 30 miles northeast of the base. The military said last week nearly 2,000 people have been killed in insurgency-related violence across the country in the first six months of the year.
