<HEAD>Eleven Killed in Battle Between Rival Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two drug-dealing gangs waged a gunfight over control of the local cocaine trade, killing 11 people and wounding dozens of others, police reported Sunday. They said the battle in the village of <LOCATION> Dos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mayo </LOCATION>, 240 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, began Thursday when a Colombian gang ambushed Peruvians as they transported about 260 pounds of cocaine paste to a rural airfield. The firefight lasted for several hours and at least six Peruvian traffickers and five Colombians were killed, according to police. Witnesses told police that dozens of people were wounded, but officials had no specific figures. A Peruvian police patrol arrived in the area shortly after the battle ended and confiscated the cocaine, according to the authorities.
