<SECOND>AM-Glenn Gould, Bjt,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exhibition Offers Intimate Look at Canada's Eccentric Musical
Genius</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 He wore a wool scarf and gloves in summer and lived like a hermit, communicating with the outside world mostly by telephone. But when <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> died of a stroke nine days after his 50th birthday in 1982, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> lost not only a notorious eccentric but one of its greatest musicians. For the first time since the pianist's death, an exhibition at the National Library in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> provides an intimate look at <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>'s life, from his checkered cloth cap to the room keys he collected at hotels across the continent, including an entire set from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Stanhope Hotel Fortunately for posterity, <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> was a pack rat who set aside one room of his apartment on <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clair </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> for scores, scripts, letters, programs, souvenirs and assorted junk. `` He wrote everything down on pads. You can almost follow him through each day,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Willis </PERSON>, head of the library's music manuscript collection The exhibit runs through mid-September. A packing list reminds <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> to bring Valium and <LOCATION> Librium </LOCATION> for his nerves, and a TV Guide. A 1966 commentary for the Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says in red ball point, `` Sometimes it seems to me that <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON> has had a rather better press than he deserves.'' A letter from his grandmother recommends a mustard pack for his sore back, and <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> commiserates with an ailing <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> -LRB- `` Dear Leonardo'' -RRB- by offering some tips on hypochondria. `` I have several titles for diseases which I am expecting to have in later life but have not yet had occasion to make use of.'' After a piano technician dislocated <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>'s shoulder with a backslap, the pianist distributed a notice requesting that no one offer to shake his hand. `` This will eliminate embarrassment all around,'' it said. A Canadian celebrity at 15, <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>'s international career had a sensational start. He landed a lucrative <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> contract the day after his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> debut in 1955, and the first of more than 100 discs, <PERSON> Bach </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Goldberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Variations </ORGANIZATION>, is still rated a classic. He suddenly abandoned the concert platform in 1964 in pursuit of what he saw as a purer musical experience in the recording studio. He eventually became his own producer, controlling a mixing board the way a conductor directs an orchestra. He loved the microphone and dedicated much of his time to radio and TV documentaries. A night owl, <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> rented a studio at <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>'s Inn on the Park because it was the only place in town he could get something to eat in the early hours, <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> said. The exhibit features <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>'s favorite Steinway, his cluttered pigeon-hole desk and the rickety card-table chair his father modified as a piano stool. <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> preferred a low-slung chair so that his fingers lay flat along the keyboard, the antithesis of the pounding romantic style he abhorred. An animal lover, <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> left his worldly goods to the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. The library was allowed to purchase the collection of 20,000 items, packed in 226 boxes, on condition it organize an exhibit. The display tours the rest of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> later this year, and negotiations are under way with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and European museums. The most personal documents were withheld, but <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> said there was evidence of `` two or three relationships'' with women that did not last long. In retrospect, <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>'s career is filled with irony. He searched for musical clarity and control in what he termed the `` backbone'' of a score and dismissed virtuoso playing and tonal beauty for its own sake. However, he marred some recordings by humming along with the music, a habit critics considered an affectation. `` Readers will find the groans and croons intolerable,'' the Penguin Guide says of one Bach recording. <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> preferred the piano to the harpsichord and played no part in the rediscovery of original instruments and pitch that has revolutionized baroque listening in the 1980s. He saw nothing wrong with splicing dozens of takes for one definitive performance and envisioned an era when recordings, adjusted electronically by home listeners, would entirely replace public concerts. <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> holds an Olympian place in Canadian music. `` As a cultural symbol, he grows in stature every year, both as a true Canadian original and as a certified hero of modernist performers,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett-Green </PERSON>, music critic for The Globe and Mail.
