RSON> <PERSON> Steiner </PERSON>, <PERSON> Barthelemy </PERSON>'s chief administrative officer. `` In kind'' contributions, with an estimated value of $ 2.5 million to $ 3 million, included use of the city's parks, a performing arts theater, the municipal auditorium and other places for meetings, office space and entertainment. Cash contributions, <PERSON> Steiner </PERSON> said, include money for a new million-dollar light system and a half-million-dollar sound system to be used by the Republicans in the Superdome. Security, including overtime for police, will eat up a lot of the money, <PERSON> Steiner </PERSON> said, along witth the cost of building stages, media platforms, seats and a raised `` false floor'' to hide cables. There's also a computer system for the convention staff, and insurance. The city's prospects for coming up with the money looked dim for a time earlier this year. The Greater New Orleans Convention Fund, headed by oil millionaire <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, was struggling. After raising about $ 2 million in contributions, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> publicly complained in May that donations were lagging. That prompted the <PERSON> Barthelemy </PERSON> administration to appoint a new committee, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> Special Events Fund, headed by <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mervin </PERSON> <PERSON> Trail </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, and by <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Moffett </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Freeport-McMoRan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> and chairman of the local Chamber of Comerce. Still assisted by <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s group, the special events fund took an aggressive, more focused approach, zeroing in on individual chamber members, the tourist and hotel industry and major corporations. So far, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said, the tactic has worked, netting contributions ranging from $ 150 from small businesses to more than $ 200,000 from major corporations. The city has so far been able to meet contractural obligations arising from construction in the dome and Republican convention officials said last week preparations for the convention were progressing on schedule.
