<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines Bjt   07-24 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines, Bjt,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bloodshed Brings Fears Of Breakdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A grisly cycle of murders and reprisal killings by leftists and rightists is raising fears of a breakdown in law and order and threatening efforts to promote democracy and protect human rights. `` Hardly a day passes without a murder or more being headlined in our newspapers,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philippines </ORGANIZATION> said in a recent statement. `` Our sensibilities are being battered day in and day out, with reportage of killings and ambuscades, of slaughter and violence _ acts of terrorism all,'' the bishops said. According to the military's <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, at least 65 people, most of them police, soldiers and anti-communist civilians, were slain in the <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> area by the rebel <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in the first six months of the year Those attacks have led to formation of right-wing `` death squads,'' which methodically target trade unionists, leftists and social activists in an apparent bid to undercut their influence in politics. Victims of the rightists include at least five Filipino human rights lawyers. A prominent leftist university president, <PERSON> Nemesio </PERSON> <PERSON> Prudente </PERSON>, has been wounded twice in two assassination attempts in the past seven months. The violence is not limited to <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Nearly 40 people have been slain this year in politically motivated violence in <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, home of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-run </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Similar killings have been reported in <LOCATION> Cebu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bacolod </LOCATION> and other major cities. Several regional officials of the pro-government <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> have dropped out of the organization in fear since the group's national chairman, <PERSON> Lean </PERSON> <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON>, was slain last September. The murder was not solved. <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON>'s group was among the social activist organizations that rallied behind <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> in the February 1986 revolt that toppled President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, who became president on the promise of restoring democracy and human rights, has called for an end to the violence. She warns that the unbridled killings will erode public confidence in her government. But Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s pledge to restore democracy has not been enough to quell the 19-year Communist insurgency, which expanded during the 20-year rule of her ousted predecessor. The killings underscore Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s fragile control of the police and armed forces. Military dissidents were responsible for a series of coup attempts that rocked the Aquino government, and leftists claim police and soldiers have been behind many of the right-wing killings. Those arrested in a June 30 attack on Prudente include five <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> policemen and a member of a government-backed anti-communist vigilante group organized by police. <PERSON> Prudente </PERSON>, who was jailed under <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> for alleged ties to a leftist assassination team, had been accused by police of harboring communists at his <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philippines </ORGANIZATION>. `` Their interpretation of democracy is some kind of police state,'' <PERSON> Prudente </PERSON> said of his attackers. `` It's no different from the communist society that they have been castigating.'' `` We are one of those victims caught in the cross fire between the extreme left and the extreme right,'' he was quoted as saying by the Sunday Inquirer Magazine. Inability to curb the violence also threatens to undermine public support for the policy of all-out war against the communists, which Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> unveiled after peace talks with the rebels collapsed in January 1987. Liberal Filipinos have begun to complain that the `` total war'' campaign is polarizing society and encouraging violence not only against doctrinaire Marxists but also against those campaigning legally for social and economic reform. `` The human rights issue calls for an urgent reassessment of the counterinsurgency policy that has forced the government to trade its humanist soul in exchange for short-term political stability provided by support of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>,'' wrote prominent columnist <PERSON> Amando </PERSON> <PERSON> Doronila </PERSON> in The <ORGANIZATION> Manila </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier this year, the rebels claimed they would scale down assassinations because of the alarm the killings generated among the urban middle class, which the communists hope to recruit to their cause. But last week, <PERSON> Arnel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandoval </PERSON>, spokesman of the rebel <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Boncayao </PERSON> <PERSON> Brigade </PERSON>, said killings would continue as long as the Aquino government fails to curb the rightists. `` As the Aquino government continues to protect and refuse to punish criminals in uniform, so shall the <ORGANIZATION> ABB </ORGANIZATION> resolve the bring these people the revolutionary justice they deserve,'' he said.
