<FIRST>r a AM-Drought-LowRiver     07-24 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought-Low River,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>River Channel Straighter, But No Longer Moves With Easy Abandon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>' efforts to tame the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> are enabling barge traffic to scrape along in spite of this summer's record low water and the river's natural tendencies, <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> officials say. `` What the river wants to do is wiggle back and forth. What we're trying to do is stabilize the channel,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, a historian with the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, Miss. Strangled by a lack of rain, the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> has dropped to more than 20 feet below normal at <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> and sand buildups have caused traffic jams involving hundreds of barges. The <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s flow is expected to fall to 20 percent of normal at <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> before the drought is over, and towboat operators say they'll lose more than $ 60 million this summer because of reduced traffic. On July 10, the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> registered a record low of 10.7 feet below zero on the river gauge at <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> and the flow of water rushing past the city was 115,000 cubic feet per second. Zero is an arbitrary mark set at 183.91 feet above sea level. At what the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> calls `` full bank,'' the flow at <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> is 1.3 million cfs and the river measures 34 feet above zero. The normal flow for July is 411,000 cfs. The record low flow of 78,000 cfs was set in 1936 when the river measured zero on the <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> gauge. Since then, the main channel has been made narrower and deeper. In the old days when the river was left to wander, the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> often split into two or more channels and formed big winding loops. In the 1930s and'40s, the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> cut off 16 of those loops to straighten the channel and shortened the Lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> by 150 miles. This year's low water has revealed stone dikes and huge concrete slabs that <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> officials say are more critical than ever to keeping the river open to barges. The dikes, sticking out into the water like long, skinny fingers, force the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s main channel toward the middle of the riverbed, while mile upon mile of concrete revetment _ a blanket of concrete slabs _ keeps the river from forming loops by eroding into the bank. The river can be more than a mile across from bank to bank, but its main channel is often only 500 to 600 feet wide. The drought has cut that to less than 200 feet in some areas. Narrowing the river and preventing it from flowing slowly around a series of bends causes the main channel to dig itself deeper. In spite of record lows, the Lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> remains 25 to 40 feet deep in some places. But towboats are running into trouble at the so-called `` crossings'' where the river channel winds back and forth across the riverbed. The current slackens and sand and sediment settle out, sometimes putting the river at less than nine feet deep, the minimum generally needed for barges and towboats. The Corps has identified more than 30 troublesome crossings where dredging will likely be needed this summer between <LOCATION> Caruthersville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, Miss.
</TEXT>
