<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Dispute Bjt   07-24 0816</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Dispute, Bjt,0843</SECOND>
<HEAD>Territorial Dispute Exposes Limits of Glasnost</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> moved away from quiet diplomacy and got tough last week as he sought to resolve a dispute over an obscure mountain region whose importance has grown far beyond its contested borders. The Soviet leader's handling of the problem offers some insight into how far he is prepared to go in allowing more openness and giving people a greater say in how they are governed. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the struggle over <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, a mostly Armenian enclave in the republic of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, has inflicted immense damage on perestroika, his reform program. He warned it could doom his plans to modernize Soviet society. Addressing the Soviet leadership Monday at a special session of the Supreme Soviet's Presidium, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said: `` If we fail to find the solution to this question today _ and we must find it _ this would have far-reaching consequences and would affect all perestroika.'' The immediate issue is the future of the sparsely populated, largely undeveloped region in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>. The ethnic Armenian majority set out in February to secede from largely Moslem <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and join predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. But in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, a patchwork quilt of 15 republics shared by more than 100 distinct ethnic and national groups, redrawing maps is a dangerous business. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and the Presidium, the top executive body of government, served notice they were not about to open that <PERSON> Pandora </PERSON>'s box. Clearly, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, or openness, is not a guarantee of free speech as practiced in Western democracies, and democratization does not sanction a challenge to one-party rule. The government has tolerated massive demonstrations _ including some in the Armenian capital of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> that have drawn hundreds of thousands, perhaps even a million people, according to witness accounts. But <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said redrawing the borders would constitute an abuse of democratization `` fundamentally at variance with the aims of perestroika.'' Giving in to nationalist demands, he told the Presidium, would `` poison public mentality with nationalist venom and thereby spoil relations between the peoples for many, many years to come.'' In unanimously rejecting <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>'s attempt to secede against <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, the Presidium warned that a series of strikes that began in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and spread to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, crippling the local economy, had exhausted the Presidium's patience. The <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> authorized police to `` take essential measures'' to end the strikes and `` activities directed at kindling national strife and attempts to misuse democratic rights for anti-democratic purposes.'' Troops stationed in the strife-torn areas were reinforced. <PERSON> Paruyr </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayrikyan </PERSON>, a leader of the annexation drive who was arrested in March on a charge of defaming the state, was stripped of his Soviet citizenship and ordered expelled from the country. The state-run national press attacked strike leaders by name. First indications showed the new tough tactics were having an impact. Most workers in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> returned to their jobs, although the general strike continued in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. The central leadership clearly has acted with more restraint and tolerance than would have been expected in previous Soviet regimes. Not long ago, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> would have quickly turned to force to put down the turmoil. This time, the Kremlin first tried the power of persuasion. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> made a personal appeal Feb. 26 for `` civic maturity and restraint,'' and the mass demonstrations in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> subsided. But two days later, a riot broke out in the Azerbaijani city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, and at least 32 people were killed, 26 of them Armenians. The <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> also tried changing the local leadership, installing new party chiefs in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. The new officials quickly acknowledged that Armenians in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> had been deprived culturally and socially under previous regimes. In March, the central government announced a major remedial program to improve cultural and social conditions in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, with much of the aid going to the Armenian majority. But Armenians outside the region, perhaps encouraged by the new latitude given them by glasnost, made annexation of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> a crusade. Those who died in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> were its martyrs. The legislatures of both <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and the Armenian republic sought the annexation, claiming the right of self-determination guaranteed by the Soviet Constitution. But <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, citing another constitutional provision requiring consent of affected republics before redrawing boundaries, rejected the appeals. That set the stage for intervention by the central government. `` Democratic rights and the new conditions opened up and created by perestroika are being clearly misused for anti-democratic purposes,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told the Presidium. Both sides, he said, were using territorial claims to stir up national sentiments and `` conceal the really difficult, crying problems that had accumulated.'' Victory can only come by finding a common course, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said, adding that the search for that course must continue.
</TEXT>
