<HEAD>Union Leaders Confident Of Vote-Getting Strength For Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Booe, graf 7, cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bolstered by their highest delegate strength ever at a Democratic convention, union leaders believe they can deliver 2.5 million votes for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in November. Although the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> will not officially endorse <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> until Aug. 24, after the Republican convention, its political operatives left here with no intention of waiting for what one called the `` pro forma announcement'' to begin working on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' behalf. An $ 8 million voter registration campaign _ put on a back burner while unions concentrated on collecting convention delegates in the primaries and caucuses _ is being reignited this week. After breakfasting with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> last week, <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> said in an interview that unions will have less difficulty than they did four years ago in getting their members to vote a Democratic ticket. `` In 1984 there was a swell of support in favor of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>,'' he said. `` We stemmed that tide better than the others. This year there is an entirely different set of circumstances. There's no incumbency and people want a change.'' Despite the union label on 1,054 or more than one-fourth of the Democratic convention delegates, labor still is maintaining a lower profile in comparison with its all-out boosterism of <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> four years ago. `` We worked harder in 1984 and all we got for it was fewer delegates and more abuse,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Booe </PERSON>, secretary-treasurer of the <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. It was two of labor's more consistent supporters in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> _ <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </P