the electorate. It calls for: _ Voter registration that is 15 percentage points above the national average of 72 percent. <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> officials estimate that about 80 percent of the federation's 14.1 million members are now registered. _ Turnout on election day that is 15 percentage points higher than the 53 percent of the voting age population that went to the polls in 1984. _ And a vote among union members for the labor-endorsed candidate that is at least 15 percentage points higher than the electorate at large gives him. The <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> achieved that in 1984 with the 61 percent of its membership voting for <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, compared with 41 percent of the total electorate. With all three, <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> estimates trade union support of a candidate is worth a net 2.5 million votes nationwide. `` That's not something to be sneezed at,'' he says with pride. According to political directors for individual unions, the effort faltered last time on making sure members were registered and getting them to the polls on election day. Even though <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> had an early lock on the labor endorsement, many believed he could not win and support waned, according to one labor activist. What's different this year is a belief among labor activists that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has so many negatives that a strong union turnout could provide <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> with the edge to beat him. `` Our rank and file by a slim margin voted for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Loretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, the Communication Workers' political director. `` But they've indicated overwhelmingly they will come back to the Democratic side. If <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> were a warm individual, the fact he has been a supporter of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would help him. But our members think he's arrogant and a snob.''
