<SECOND>AM-Mink Creek Fire, Bjt,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Limited War Waged On Stubborn Forest Fire In Wyoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN MOSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bloodshot eyes, a hoarse voice and a weary demeanor are hallmarks of <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>'s profession, a result of working 15 hours or more at a time in the acrid smoke and intense heat of forest fires. Injury or death are possible. The pay is marginal, an average of about $ 8 an hour. Except for an occasional good meal, the only benefit may be a shower after a shift. For more than a week now, <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> has led crews battling the <ORGANIZATION> Mink </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> fire, which by Sunday had blackened 22,650 acres in the Teton Wilderness of the <ORGANIZATION> Bridger-Teton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> 40 miles northeast of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` It's just so dry,'' incident commander <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarrell </PERSON> said Friday. `` We just have to have some rain. But our weather people say there's nothing in the forecast for at least 10 days, and we're also facing the prospect of some dry lightning strikes in the next few days. Wind gusting to 35 mph and humidity as low as 11 percent have exacerbated the dry conditions. The main thrust of efforts by firefighters _ as many as 830 but down to 737 Sunday _ has been to prevent the fire from spreading south, where it could threaten homes and dude ranches in <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. The firefighters' line across the southern end was holding Sunday, but the north end had burned about a quarter of a mile into Yellowstone National Park. Officials said it was in a remote area more than 30 miles from any major park attractions, but other fires burned inside the park. The southern edge of the huge blaze was about five miles from <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, but in between is an area of `` blowdown'' trees, piles of tinder-dry wood left by a tornado last year. `` We're holding on at the south end, and every day we do that is a real positive,'' said <PERSON> Jarrell </PERSON>. The lightning-caused blaze broke out July 11 and because it is in a wilderness area, officials are required by law to allow it to burn its natural course as much as possible. Such blazes are usually allowed to burn until they threaten human life or private property. In the long run, officials say, wildlife benefits. With the threat to residents south of the fire, crews have taken a more active role. However, they are restricted in their digging and cutting, and the use of bulldozers and mechanical tools such as chain saws is discouraged. All work must be done by air or on foot; there is no vehicle access. The cost of fighting the blaze was just over $ 2 million Sunday, forestry officials said. `` Any wilderness fire is more difficult to fight because of its remoteness,'' said <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, who has been fighting fires since 1968. `` The constraints make it even harder.'' In addition to digging fire lines, crews deployed 20 miles of hose to draw water from lakes and ponds. They also burned 2,000 acres to create a fire break on the southern edge. <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, 39, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> range conservationist from <LOCATION> Vale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, said some firefighters have experienced knee and leg problems because of the steep terrain. But morale, he said, `` has been fantastic. These teams have a lot of pride.'' For the past few days, <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> has been leader of a group of <LOCATION> Chippewa </LOCATION> Indian firefighters from <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. That crew just arrived from battling another blaze in Lame Deer, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>. The base camp has facilities for eating, sleeping, caring for the injured and organizing the firefighting. Officials pore over maps and infrared photographs of the fire area. Health and safety officials monitor fatigue among crews, shipping some out for a rest and demobilizing others entirely, bringing in fresh crews to replace them. A fresh crew could expect to stay on the scene as long as 21 days. `` I'll be here that long if my legs hold out,'' <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said.
