<FIRST>u a AM-SchoolReform Bjt   07-24 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Reform, Bjt,0732</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reform Package Would Give Local Schools Autonomy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The school system branded the worst in the nation could become a trailblazer under a reform package that calls for a slimmed-down bureaucracy and more neighborhood clout. The proposal calls for a council at each of the city's 594 schools to create a three-year improvement plan. If the called-for changes are n't made, the council may fire the principal. The councils will consist of 11 members _ parents, teachers, community residents and the principal. Decentralization of power in public schools is a national trend, but no district has given schools the kind of autonomy outlined in this package, authorities say. `` Even though it's been talked about a few times in the country, I think if <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> goes ahead, it will be a unique step,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Pipho </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> of the States, a Denver-based non-profit group that monitors school legislation. The reform bill for <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s beleaguered schools was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> this spring and awaits Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s signature <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> must decide by September but has not indicated which way he's leaning. If he signs, it will take effect next July. Critics say the measure focuses too much on administrative reorganization and too little on programs to help boost performance of the 430,000 students in the nation's third-largest school district. Even supporters say that if the measure accomplishes all that's intended, it wo n't cure deep-seated ills like the growing numbers of low-income students, a double-digit dropout rate and teen-age pregnancy `` We'd be kidding ourselves to think that simply doing this is going to do all those other things that affect learning,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakalis </PERSON>, dean of the education school at <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the state's former education superintendent. But <PERSON> Bakalis </PERSON>, who co-chaired a coalition of community groups that fought to reform <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> schools, called the package `` a first step'' toward eliminating problems that have given the system a national reputation for mediocrity. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who last year labeled <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> schools the nation's worst, has not yet studied the package and is `` inclined not to comment until enough time has passed'' to assess the results, said a spokesman, <PERSON> Loye </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. The schools' problems stem largely from poorly trained teachers and administrators ill-equipped to handle the 70 percent of the student population from poor homes, said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Oppenhiemer </PERSON>, executive director of the pro-reform group <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schools </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` The fact is that children bring many more problems to school than they used to _ health problems, language deficiencies, just coming to school without the same kind of nurturing at home that they had when it was a typical two-parent family situation ... where children were talked to, where parents were very much involved,'' he said Friday. He said the reform measure will help by permitting speedier removal of unsatisfactory personnel. Also under the bill, a teacher could be dismissed after 45 days for unsatisfactory performance, <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> said. Teachers now found to be doing a poor job by the principal and a consulting teacher are given a year to improve. However, the measure does not provide additional money for retraining teachers or administrators, Oppenheimer noted. `` It's fine to get rid of lousy teachers But it's better to retrain ... and teacher retraining takes money,'' he said. The package also would allow principals to hire teachers on merit, without regard for seniority, reduce administrative spending and staff at the city <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> and create a board to oversee the changes. Many have mixed feelings about the degree of parental involvement called for in the package. `` I do n't feel that parents will have the time or the know-how, nor the interest, to become that involved,'' said <PERSON> Francoise </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, who heads a pro-reform group called Concerned Parents Network. `` I am a very active parent ... and I know how difficult it is to get parents involved,'' she said. The school board and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> have declined to endorse or reject the proposal. `` The entire bill is under review'' by the board's legal department, said spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Saigh </PERSON>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kotsakis </PERSON>, assistant to <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Vaughn </PERSON>, the union president, declined comment. `` We have n't seen the final and actual language,'' he said.
