<TEXT>
 Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, trying to bolster his standing among women voters, on Sunday proposed a wide-ranging child-care proposal that could give low-income families government checks of up to $ 1,000 per child. The proposed program would cost $ 2.2 billion a year and eventually apply to all families with children under age 4 in which at least one parent worked, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Families who did n't get a government check would get a tax credit, under the plan <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> outlined the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> and Profession Women's Clubs. At first, it would apply only to low-income families, and would be phased in over four years to include higher-income households. Initial reaction to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal was favorable, but tempered with criticism of his overall record on women's issues. `` This is one of his first concrete gestures'' toward women, said federation president <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Wray </PERSON>. Asked how she would rate the speech, she replied: `` As far as addressing our issues, he escalated on any scale. But as far as addressing the kinds of things we'd like to see advanced, he did n't come close to a 10. After <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s speech, many members of the audience chanted `` E-R-A,'' a reference to the Equal Rights Amendment, which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> opposes. The vice president said the tax credit, which would be in addition to the existing child care tax credit and the federal deduction for dependents, is designed `` to recognize the increased costs of families with children.'' There would be no strings attached to the tax credit and it would apply equally to those who paid for outside child care and those who did n't. `` As businesswomen, I do n't need to tell you that child care is a significant business expense,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the audience, made up of about 2,500 professional women. The certain <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> presidential nominee, who has proposed an overall freeze on federal spending at the rate of inflation, did not specify how his wide-ranging proposals would be financed. He was accompanied to the speech by former <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, a frequently mentioned vice presidential possibility. Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, wife of former <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> rival <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, accompanied <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> here aboard Air Force Two, and, according to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides, helped worked on the final draft of his speech. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said that there was no discussion during the flight of the vice presidential selection process. Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> spoke to the convention after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s criticized a $ 2.5 billion day-care proposal now before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> _ and favored by Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> _ that would provide direct government assistance to day-care providers. It would not be limited to low-income families. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s child-care program included: _ Expansion of the existing child-care tax credit to cover more low-families, at a cost of $ 400 million a year _ Creation of work-place child-care centers for all government employees, modeled after a program begun by Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, and a federally underwritten liability insurance program for private centers, costing $ 50 million a year _ More federal assistance to help states and local governments set up programs such as sick child care and before-and-after school care, at a cost of $ 250 million <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposals received polite, but scattered, applause from the bipartisan audience. `` I'm not going to give you a political speech,'' he declared. However, he told the audience that `` one of my attributes for president is I did what many of you did _ I started a business.'' `` The expanded role for women in the work force is dramatic. It is the single most important demographic change in the second half of the 20th century,'' he said. But still, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> noted that women still earn only 70 cents for every dollar earned by men. He said that, while this was up from the 59 cents of just a few years ago, `` there is only one amount that women should earn for every dollar earned by a man _ and that is one dollar.'' Members of the audience cheered this remark loudly and waved red purses, a symbol of the disparity in pay between genders. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was presented with such a purse. Campaign aides depicted the speech as a major effort to underscore <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s commitment to issues affecting working women. His campaign has been making a push to improve his standing among women voters, shown by a series of polls to be a weak point for him. Republican analysts have said that part of the `` gender gap'' problem _ which also afflicted President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in both 1980 and 1984 _ reflects voter registration breakdown: a greater proportion of women are Democrats than men. However, some women's groups have accused <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, as well as the overall <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, of insensitivity to women's issues and other social concerns and an overemphasis on defense issues. Asked why <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not mention the Equal Rights Amendemnt in his talk, aide <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Steelman </PERSON> said, `` These are today's relevant issues.'' But <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Forbes </PERSON>, president-elect of the organization, said, `` He may be beyond it -LRB- the ERA -RRB- but we are not.''
