<HEAD>Stepfather Sentenced To Six Years In Prison After Girl Recants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINTER GARDEN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prosecutors have refused to grant immunity from perjury charges to a 14-year-old girl who recanted sex abuse charges against her stepfather before he was sentenced to six years in prison. The girl now says she lied two years ago when she initially told of the alleged abuse and lied again in April before the jury that convicted her stepfather because she was afraid of going to jail for perjury. She is working with her mother to get her stepfather a new trial by raising money to hire a lawyer for an appeal. The mother and daughter publicized their cause over the weekend by being interviewed by The Orlando Sentinel, but the identities of the two adults and the girl were not revealed in keeping with state law. Prosecutors contend the mother indirectly pressured the girl into recanting. Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> said the reason for refusing to grant her immunity, however, is that to do so would condone lying. The girl either lied when she made up the charges, or would have been lying when she recanted, the prosecutor said. `` It undermines the whole system,'' Ms. <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> said. `` Why should we say it's OK to lie? It's not our policy to grant immunity to people you think are telling lies under that immunity.'' Judge <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Formet </PERSON>, in what he called one of the toughest decisions he has made in nine years on the bench, denied the 34-year-old man's motion for a new trial. And he sentenced him to six years in prison on charges of lewd assault, although he had been informed the girl had recanted. The mother steadfastly denies pressuring her daughter to recant, and the daughter said the only pressure came from prosecutors angered by her decision to recant. The case began when the girl broke down in tears to her elementary school teacher in March 1986, right after a police officer had talked to her class about sexual abuse by parents and relatives. Now she says she made up the story because she wanted more time with her mother. `` It seemed like my mom paid a lot more attention when he was gone,'' the girl said. The girl met privately with the prosecutor, Ms. <PERSON> Heller </PERSON>, on June 1, the day of the sentencing, and told her she was lying. `` I was looking right at her,'' the girl said. `` She said, ` You could n't have lied that long.' She said, ` You're lying, you're lying' and hit the table She scared me.'' Ms. <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> disagreed with the girl's version. `` I never yelled at her,'' <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> said. `` I was trying to get her to explain why she waited until the sentencing to tell me. If I seemed angry, it was n't at her. I was upset that this was happening.''
