<FIRST>u a AM-InsulationDanger 1stLd-Writethru a0772 07-24 0844</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insulation Danger, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0772,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wiring Insulation Implicated in Fighter, Shuttle Fires</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Monday reports, RECAST to
avoid implying that investigators fixed blame on Kapton a dozen
times, DELETE reference to taking advice of contractors which does
not reflect newspaper's characterization, CORRECT shuttle incident
to 1983 sted 1985, and ADD more on Air Force viewpoint. Picks up
5th graf pvs `Virtually All...' INSERTS 4 grafs after 9th graf `The
heat' to add Air Force and FAA comment. Subs 14th graf pvs `Lubert
Legar' to CORRECT year.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wiring insulation has been implicated in fires in at least 12 military and commercial aircraft models, but the hazard may actually be much more widespread, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star-Telegram </ORGANIZATION>, in stories published Sunday and in an early Monday edition, said the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> was slow to notify its flight crews about dangers associated with the insulation, called <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON>, under certain conditions. <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> also was used on the space shuttle, and may have caused a fire during maintenance in 1983 that was n't blamed on insulation at the time, the newspaper said. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> banned <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> in 1986 after documenting in laboratory tests that it can explode in flames and disable crucial flight-control systems. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> restricts <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> use only in high-vibration areas of new aircraft and recently issued a ban on its use in repairs. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> contends that the conditions necessary for such an explosion to occur rarely exist except in laboratory tests and that it is impossible to determine whether the insulation was to blame for electrical fires in years gone by. Virtually all contractors who provide <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aircraft to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> use <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> extensively, the newspaper said. No known deaths have been caused by insulation-related aircraft fires through almost two decades of the insulation's use in more than 50 kinds of aircraft. The newspaper reviewed 265 field reports dealing with electrical problems on the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> F-16 and found at least 45 instances between 1978 and 1986 of wire fires or severe arcing. Included are six in-flight emergencies and two incidents considered potentially life-threatening by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION>, maker of the F-16. The single-engine fighters, which rely on electrical impulses to control their flight rather than mechanical wires and pulleys, each contains 10 miles of Kapton-coated wire, more than 85 percent of the aircraft's wiring. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> laboratory studies in 1984 and 1985 found that <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON>, a carbon-based film, can explode under certain conditions when exposed to an electrical arc. The heat of the arc causes the insulation to carbonize _ instantly deteriorate into a charry substance _ and form a conductive path for the arc to spread to adjacent wires in an instantaneous explosion known as `` flashover,'' or `` arc tracking.'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rall </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s top civilian engineer, said flashover can only be documented by `` trained experts.'' <PERSON> Rall </PERSON> warned personnel about Kaptan in a newsletter dated March, 26, 1986, but concluded that it was `` an acceptable aircraft wire insulation given proper installation and maintenance procedures.'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s Technical Center in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said the agency is considering issuing guidelines on <LOCATION> Kapton </LOCATION> usage in commercial aircraft, such as recommending against its use in areas that are susceptible to moisture. `` We do not believe there's enough information that says you should ban <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> and take it out of the airplane,'' he said. `` We do think there is enough of a problem or a potential problem that we should make some changes.'' <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> began to gain popularity in the early and mid-1970s, first in the military and later in commercial aviation. Proponents said <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> was the perfect insulator, being small enough to fit into tight spaces on fighter jets, light enough to save precious fuel on airliners and strong enough, as required by government specifications, to last `` for the life of the aircraft.'' But as the insulation was put into service, maintenance crews initially complained that <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON> was stiff, brittle and fragile and broke easily when bent. They argued that it was difficult to work with and required too much `` mothering'' to be practical. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, a spokesman for E.I. du <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nemours </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes <PERSON> Kapton </PERSON>, contends that any insulation will arc-track in the presence of conductive fluid. <PERSON> Lubert </PERSON> <PERSON> Leger </PERSON>, head of the materials branch for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, said a 1983 arcing incident aboard the shuttle <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> during maintenance may have been initially misdiagnosed. Contractor <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s investigation of the incident listed the cause of the fire as `` not apparent,'' but <PERSON> Leger </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Star-Telegram </ORGANIZATION> said it had all the earmarks of a Kapton-related flashover. At least 100 aircraft electrical fires reported over the past 15 years have occurred under circumstances that bear striking similarities to <LOCATION> Kapton </LOCATION> failures, aircraft maintenance records and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> field studies suggest. Records cite initial damage to one or two wires followed by arcing that spreads the fire to adjacent wires.
