<HEAD>Tumultuous Year Continues At Polaroid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which first gave the world instant snapshots more than half a century ago, has been thrust into the public eye in 1988 by a series of high-stakes events that portend significant changes for the company. On Wall Street, analysts and arbitragers are fascinated by the possibility of an all-out takeover battle for <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>, prompted by a hostile bid last week from a California-based investment group led by an heir to the Disney entertainment empire. In the courts, the outcome of a $ 5.7 billion patent infringement suit against rival <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> could have a major impact on <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> stock prices. And in its headquarters along the <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, company officials are trimming the work force while preparing to challenge <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> and other film manufacturers with the worldwide introduction of conventional color film. Polaroid, with a reputation for extravagant research and uninspired marketing, now faces quick and important decisions. `` We're all waiting to see what happens,'' said <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Polaroid is hot right now.'' <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s tumultuous year began dramatically in late February with its $ 5.7 billion damage claim in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> patent suit. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> claims it lost $ 3.2 billion in sales and $ 2.5 billion in business opportunities after <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> entered the instant camera field in 1976. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> Rya </PERSON> <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON> ruled in 1985 that <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> violated seven Polaroid patents and ordered the <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based company to halt production of the instant film and camera. <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON> last month withdrew from the 12-year-old case due to family holdings of <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> stock. The damages portion of the case is scheduled to be heard in January with a new judge presiding. Although <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> termed the damage claim `` ludicrous and ridiculously inflated,'' <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> stock has risen sharply from the mid - $ 20 range in anticipation of a decision in <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s favor Polaroid closed at $ 40.75 a share Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, largely because of takeover talk. The company would welcome any award _ even the $ 1 billion to $ 2 billion many analysts predict _ following several years of lackluster performance. Polaroid camera sales have dropped nearly 50 percent from a high of 7.5 million in 1978, and the public has poorly received several new products, such as video film. Polaroid was formed in 1937 by Dr. <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Land </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> to develop and manufacture a synthetic light polarizing material he developed. Polaroid produced instant color photography in 1963 and made its most stunning achievement in 1972 with the release of the SX-70 system, which produced instant pictures outside the camera. It has made ventures in other market areas but with nowhere near the success of its breakthroughs in instant photography. Amid takeover rumors, the company on July 12 announced a reorganization plan highlighted by 500 to 800 layoffs and its entry into the $ 7 billion-a-year conventional film market. Company officials would not announce when the new film will be available outside <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, where it has been sold for two years in direct competition with industry leaders <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Agfa-Gevaert </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Fuji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Photo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Ltd Meanwhile, the layoffs mark the latest in a decade-long reduction in <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s work force, which has declined from more than 20,000 in 1978 to nearly 13,000. A company statement said most employees could select either early retirement or a severance plan that provided up to one year's salary. In addition, the company issued 10 million new shares into an employee stock ownership plan and launched a $ 300 million company stock repurchase effort. The move was interpreted as an effort to discourage takeover attempts. But less than a week later, <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a television and radio concern based in <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, made a $ 40-per-share bid for <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> and filed suit in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> seeking to cancel the employee stock purchase plan. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>, owned by the family of <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Disney </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> director and nephew of the famous animator, disclosed on July 20 it had acquired 4.93 million Polaroid shares as of May 11. Its takeover bid values the company at about $ 2.88 billion if all 71.9 million shares remain outstanding. However, <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> has indicated it might not proceed unless it manages to get the recent 10 million-share issue rolled back. In that case, the implied value of the bid would be $ 2.48 billion. Because <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> already owns a large block, its cost to buy the rest would be $ 2.28 billion, assuming defeat of the share issue, or $ 2.68 billion if the share issue is not defeated. According to <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> documents, <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> President and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> MacAllister </PERSON> <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> refused to meet with <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year to discuss company strategies. Booth eventually consented to a July 13 meeting on condition that <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> would not acquire additional <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> stock, and <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> in turn take no action which might hurt <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>'s investment. The meeting was not held in the wake of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s reorganization announcement, which <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> termed a `` clear breach'' of its agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> The company said it would convene directors Tuesday to discuss the Shamrock bid. Some analysts are skeptical the 10-year-old Shamrock group could put together a deal of such magnitude. Earlier this year, <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> failed in a $ 92 million bid for <ORGANIZATION> Wherehouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> video rental and music company. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> owns Music Plus, a 54-store music and video retail chain in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area, in addition to three television stations and 14 radio stations. `` As far as I'm concerned it's a very shaky bid,'' said <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON>. `` There seems to be too many conditions attatched to the offer ... It just seems out of their league.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Relyea </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> could have a major impact on investors if it could arrange a tender offer at a lower price with a promise to distribute any dividends to shareholders following resolution of the <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> suit. `` Say, for example, they got Polaroid for $ 30 a share,'' said <PERSON> Relyea </PERSON>. `` Well, that would set the damage award at about $ 10 a share, when right now no one can really say what effect it will have.'' The offer by <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> also could lure other suitors, hostile or friendly, into the bidding for <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>, analysts say.
