<HEAD>Hunts Offer Debt Settlement For Placid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Hunt brothers' <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oil operation has offered to pay $ 803.5 million to settle the final step in a bitter two-year court battle between Hunt companies and banks that lent them $ 1.5 billion, according to company officials. The offer by <ORGANIZATION> Placid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which is owned by <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> trust estates, includes cash repayments of $ 663.5 million over the next two months. The Hunts also would to pay the banks $ 140 million from Placid production revenues during the next seven years, company officials said Saturday. The plan, which is subject to approval by federal bankruptcy court, <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and major creditor groups, nearly would complete the settlement of the case and would remove Placid from bankruptcy protection. It also would leave the billionaire <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> brothers with only pieces of the vast petroleum-based empire amassed by their father, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> wildcatter H.L. Hunt. Late in June, the Hunt trusts and bank creditors agreed on a settlement to resolve issues surrounding some $ 760 million in loans to their <ORGANIZATION> Penrod </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drilling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Penrod </PERSON>, the world's biggest independent offshore oil-drilling company, and <ORGANIZATION> Placid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> sued 23 of their lenders for fraud and misrepresentation in 1986 after defaulting on $ 1.5 billion in bank loans Two of the banks since have been dropped from the case. The suit sought $ 14 million in damages, alleging the banks conspired to drive <PERSON> Penrod </PERSON> and Placid out of business by forcing them to agree to an unreasonable payment schedule while offering their competitors more favorable terms. In August 1986, the trust estates of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection for the trust partnership that owns <ORGANIZATION> Penrod </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drilling </ORGANIZATION>. The reorganization plan proposed for Placid calls for sale of the Hunt brothers' interests in the 60-story Thanksgiving Tower, a downtown <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> office building, and disposal of Hunt production properties in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, transactions that are completed or pending. `` It depends on a number of large transactions,'' Hunt attorney <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said of the proposal. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said one obstacle to conclusion of the settlement was the negotiation under way in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> for a loan of about $ 245 million, to be secured by <ORGANIZATION> Placid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>, the Hunts' <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> unit The Hunts already have paid $ 213.5 million of the proposed $ 663.5 million cash settlement from funds raised through Placid operations, primarily the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> unit, as part of cash collateral agreements with bank lenders, said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>. Another $ 150 million was raised through sale of the Hunts' <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> oil and gas fields in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, he said. The brothers also plan to apply to the settlement their share of the $ 50 million in proceeds expected from pending sale of an 80 percent interest in Thanksgiving Tower. The planned sale of the building to <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ